  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a broad and unequivocal consensus that money laundering is illegal worldwide. Money laundering is the process of concealing the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by means of transfers involving foreign banks or legitimate businesses. It is universally recognized as a criminal activity because it enables the proceeds of crime to be disguised and integrated into the legitimate financial system, perpetuating criminal enterprises and undermining the integrity of financial institutions.\n\nVirtually all countries have enacted laws and regulations to combat money laundering, often in alignment with international standards set by organizations such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF). These laws typically require financial institutions to implement anti-money laundering (AML) measures, such as customer due diligence, transaction monitoring, and reporting suspicious activities. Penalties for money laundering can include significant fines, asset seizure, and imprisonment.\n\nThe global consensus against money laundering is reinforced by international cooperation and treaties aimed at combating financial crimes. For example, the United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (the Palermo Convention) and the United Nations Convention against Corruption both include provisions related to preventing and prosecuting money laundering.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is universally recognized as illegal, and there is a strong international commitment to preventing and prosecuting this activity.",
